                ğŸ” Authentication in Integrations
           
Authentication
â”œâ”€â”€ 1. OAuth 2.0 Flows (Most Common)
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ A. Web Server Flow
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Used by apps with UI
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Redirects user to Salesforce login
â”‚   â”‚   â””â”€â”€ Requires client ID/secret + authorization code exchange
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ B. JWT Bearer Flow
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Server-to-server integration (no UI)
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Uses digital certificate (private key) to sign JWT
â”‚   â”‚   â””â”€â”€ Ideal for secure backend apps or middleware
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ C. Username-Password Flow
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Legacy
â”‚   â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Direct login using stored credentials
â”‚   â”‚   â””â”€â”€ Not recommended (hard to secure, MFA issues)
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ D. Device Flow
â”‚   â”‚   â””â”€â”€ Used for IoT or devices without browser
â”‚
â”œâ”€â”€ 2. Named Credentials (Wrapper Around Auth)
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Abstracts OAuth / Basic Auth / Custom Header
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Auto manages token refresh
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ Used in Apex + External Services

â”œâ”€â”€ 3. Session ID (Legacy)
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Uses current user session (not safe for long-term)
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ Avoid for production use

â”œâ”€â”€ 4. API Keys / Custom Tokens
â”‚   â”œâ”€â”€ Sometimes used in outbound calls
â”‚   â””â”€â”€ Often sent in headers (e.g., `Authorization: Bearer <token>`)

